# Git Commit and Push Approval

## Critical Rule

**NEVER commit or push any changes without explicit user approval.**

## Required Workflow

1. **Before committing:**
   - Ask the user for explicit approval
   - Show what files will be committed
   - Wait for user confirmation

2. **Before pushing:**
   - Ask the user for explicit approval
   - Show the commits that will be pushed
   - Wait for user confirmation

3. **User must explicitly say:**
   - "yes", "commit", "push", "approved", or similar affirmative
   - Before any git commit or push command is executed

## Prohibited Actions

- Do NOT run `git commit` without approval
- Do NOT run `git push` without approval
- Do NOT use `--no-verify` to bypass hooks without approval
- Do NOT force push (`--force`, `-f`) without approval
- Do NOT amend commits (`--amend`) without approval

## Safe Actions (No Approval Required)

- `git status` - Check status
- `git log` - View history
- `git diff` - View changes
- `git add` - Stage files (but still need approval to commit)
- `git fetch` - Fetch remote changes
- `git pull` - Pull changes
- `git branch` - List branches
- `git stash` - Stash changes

## Approval Checklist

Before running any commit or push:
- [ ] User has explicitly approved
- [ ] Files to be committed are shown to user
- [ ] Commit message is reviewed by user (if provided)
